    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "Cl[Zn]Cl",
      "Cl"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic textbook example of the Houben-Hoesch reaction, featuring the acylation of a highly activated, electron-rich aromatic ring (1,3,5-trimethoxybenzene) with a simple nitrile (acetonitrile). The reaction is catalyzed by a Lewis acid (ZnCl2) and a protic acid (HCl). The product is a simple aryl ketone, 2,4,6-trimethoxyacetophenone. This example clearly illustrates the key transformation: the formation of a C(aryl)-C(acyl) bond using a nitrile as the acylating agent.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple, highly activated arene (1,3,5-trimethoxybenzene) and a simple nitrile (acetonitrile), which are characteristic of the Houben-Hoesch reaction. It avoids using phenol itself, which could be ambiguous with reactions like the Fries rearrangement. The use of a nitrile as the acylating agent distinguishes it from the Friedel-Crafts acylation, which typically uses acyl halides or anhydrides. The acyclic nature of the reactants and product minimizes potential collisions with intramolecular or ring-forming reactions."
  }
}
